0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book investigates the relationship between English and personal and national development, as this is both discursively promoted (particularly through language policy) and practically realized in developing societies. It addresses the effects that the increased use of English and the promotion of English-language education are having in developmental contexts, and their impact on broader educational issues, on local language ecologies and on questions of cultural identity. It investigates these issues by drawing together a series of original examinations and case studies by a range of leading scholars working in this burgeoning field. The chapters focus on a variety of contexts from around the world, and the volume as a whole surveys and critiques the positioning and influence of English as a catalyst for development in the 21st century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnglish languagexGlobalization. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teachingxForeign countries. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teachingzForeign countries. 0aEnglish languagexStudy and teaching. 0aEnglish languagexVariation. 0aLanguage and languagesxPolitical aspects. 0aLanguage policyxEnglish-speaking countries. 0aLanguage policyzEnglish-speaking countries. 7aEDUCATION / Bilingual Education.2bisacsh  aEnglish as a lingua franca.  aEnglish language education.  aEnglish language teaching.  aEnglish-medium instruction.  acultural identity.  aglobalisation.  aglobalization.  ainternational development.  alanguage development.  alanguage policies.  alocal language ecologies.1 aAhimbisibwe, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArcand, Jean-Louis, econtributor.4ctb4htt